(:kind :chapter :book "Reference Manual" :chapter-number 15 :title "Chapter 15 — Testing in Scheme" :source-path "git://origin/main/scheme-books/reference/15-testing-in-scheme.md" :size 6144 :sha256 "1b88510841e86b49" :content "---\nslug: sakura-scheme-book-reference-15\ntitle: Testing in Scheme\nbook: reference\nchapter: 15\nof: 16\npart: II\napp: scheme-repl\npalette: book-standard\ncanonical: true\nowner: docs-team (Lane 6)\nphilosopher-lens: [wittgenstein-tractatus, jung, lacan, peirce, popper, freud, wittgenstein-late, searle]\nstatus: draft\nlast-reviewed: 2026-07-12\nprev: 14-a-small-typechecker\nnext: 16-closing-the-reference\n---\n\n# Chapter 15 — Testing in Scheme\n\nEvery function you've written in this book could be tested. Some\nwere; most weren't shown that way. This chapter is about writing\ntests that keep working code working — a *falsifier* for the\nprogram in the Popper sense. A test says \"if this program stops\ncomputing the right answer, I'll fail.\" If the test never fails,\neither the program is right or the test is wrong.\n\nThe test shape in Scheme is simple: a small program that runs\nyour function and compares the result to what you expected. The\ndiscipline is what makes it useful.\n\n## The smallest test framework\n\n```scheme\n(define test-count 0)\n(define fail-count 0)\n\n(define (test name got expected)\n  (set! test-count (+ test-count 1))\n  (if (equal? got expected)\n      (display (string-append \"  ok — \" name \"\\n\"))\n      (begin\n        (set! fail-count (+ fail-count 1))\n        (display (string-append \"  FAIL — \" name \"\\n\"))\n        (display (string-append \"    expected: \" (repr expected) \"\\n\"))\n        (display (string-append \"    got:      \" (repr got) \"\\n\")))))\n\n(define (test-summary)\n  (display (string-append \"\\n\"\n             (number->string (- test-count fail-count))\n             \"/\"\n             (number->string test-count)\n             \" tests passed\\n\")))\n```\n\nTwenty lines. Enough to test everything in this book. `test` takes\na name, an actual, and an expected. Reports pass or fail. At the\nend, `test-summary` prints the tally.\n\n## A test suite for a function\n\n```scheme\n;; Function under test:\n(define (factorial n)\n  (if (<= n 1) 1 (* n (factorial (- n 1)))))\n\n;; The suite:\n(test \"factorial-0\" (factorial 0) 1)\n(test \"factorial-1\" (factorial 1) 1)\n(test \"factorial-5\" (factorial 5) 120)\n(test \"factorial-10\" (factorial 10) 3628800)\n\n(test-summary)\n```\n\nFour tests. Each names a specific case. Each has the same shape:\nrun the function, compare to expected. When the function is\nwrong, the failing tests point at the specific case that broke.\n\n## Testing the evaluator (Chapter 13)\n\n```scheme\n(test \"eval-num\"    (eval-expr (num 5) '()) 5)\n(test \"eval-add\"    (eval-expr (add (num 3) (num 4)) '()) 7)\n(test \"eval-let\"    (eval-expr (letex 'x (num 3)\n                                       (mul (var 'x) (num 4))) '())\n                    12)\n(test \"eval-nested\" (eval-expr (letex 'x (num 3)\n                                       (letex 'y (num 4)\n                                              (add (var 'x) (var 'y)))) '())\n                    7)\n```\n\nThe tests document the language *and* verify it. If someone\nextends the evaluator and one of these breaks, they know\nimmediately.\n\n## Property-based tests\n\nFor some functions, you don't want to enumerate cases — you want\nto check a *property* over many inputs. A quick random-input\ntester:\n\n```scheme\n(define (random-int)\n  (- (random 200) 100))\n\n(define (property-test name predicate n)\n  (let loop ((i 0) (failures 0))\n    (if (>= i n)\n        (test name (= failures 0) #t)\n        (let ((x (random-int)) (y (random-int)))\n          (if (predicate x y)\n              (loop (+ i 1) failures)\n              (loop (+ i 1) (+ failures 1)))))))\n\n(property-test \"add-is-commutative\"\n  (lambda (x y) (= (+ x y) (+ y x)))\n  100)\n\n(property-test \"factorial-nonneg\"\n  (lambda (x _) (> (factorial (abs x)) 0))\n  50)\n```\n\nProperty tests are useful when the property is easy to state\ngenerally. They're weaker than case-based tests in that they\ndon't pin down specific expected values, but they cover a wider\ninput space.\n\n## Testing programs that read the world\n\nSome code reaches out — hits an API, reads a file, calls a\nservice. Testing that code directly means the tests get slow and\nflaky. The move: separate the reaching from the reasoning, test\nthe reasoning with fake inputs.\n\n```scheme\n;; Not this — hard to test:\n(define (get-shipping-status)\n  (http-get \"https://api.carrier.com/track/4132\"))\n\n;; This — easy to test:\n(define (interpret-shipping-status response)\n  (cond\n    ((eq? (assq 'status response) 'delivered) 'delivered)\n    ((eq? (assq 'status response) 'in-transit) 'in-transit)\n    (else 'unknown)))\n\n(test \"interpret-delivered\"\n  (interpret-shipping-status '((status . delivered)))\n  'delivered)\n\n(test \"interpret-unknown\"\n  (interpret-shipping-status '((status . weird)))\n  'unknown)\n```\n\n`interpret-shipping-status` is pure. Feed it any input, test any\ncase. `get-shipping-status` is where the world is; you test it\nwith an integration test or by wrapping the call in a mock.\n\n## What tests are *not* for\n\nTests aren't a substitute for reading code carefully. Tests aren't\na proof of correctness. Tests don't tell you the design is good.\nThey tell you: given these inputs, this output. Every other\nquestion is yours.\n\n## Sakura's register on testing\n\nShe writes tests as she goes, especially for functions that will\nbe called from other functions. She doesn't test every helper.\nShe tests the seams. When she fixes a bug, she writes the test\nthat would have caught it *before* fixing the bug. That way the\ntest protects against regression.\n\n> **Sakura says**\n>\n> A test is a small program that says \"if this bigger program\n> stops working, I'll fail.\" It's cheap protection against\n> forgetting. I write them for anything I'll come back to.\n\n## Exercises\n\n1. Write tests for `deriv` from Chapter 12. Cover numbers,\n   variables, sums, products, and nested cases.\n2. Write a property test that `deriv` always returns something\n   that evaluates to the correct derivative at a specific point.\n3. Refactor `interpret-shipping-status` above to handle a\n   \"held-at-customs\" status. Write the test first.\n4. Give a test that catches a bug in `factorial` if someone\n   changes it to `(* n (factorial n))`. What's the smallest\n   input that catches it?\n")
